---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "EBITDA vs Net Income: What's the Difference?",
  description: "Compare EBITDA vs Net Income side-by-side. Understand when to use each metric and what they tell you about a company's profitability.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-17",
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "EBITDA vs Net Income: What's the Difference?",
    "description": "Compare EBITDA vs Net Income side-by-side. Understand when to use each metric and what they tell you about a company's profitability.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Is EBITDA the same as Net Income?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "text": "No. Net income is the absolute 'bottom line' profit after all expenses, including interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization. EBITDA adds those four non-operating expenses back into net income."
            }
      },
      {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Can a company have positive EBITDA but negative net income?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "text": "Yes. If a company has high depreciation from heavy capital investments or high interest payments from heavy debt, those expenses can push net income below zero even if operations generate positive cash (EBITDA)."
            }
      },
      {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Which is better for valuation: EBITDA or Net Income?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "text": "EBITDA is often preferred for valuing companies (e.g., EV/EBITDA) because it normalizes differences in capital structure and tax rates, making it easier to compare businesses."
            }
      }
]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/ebitda-vs-net-income" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>EBITDA vs Net Income: What's the Difference?</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Compare EBITDA vs Net Income side-by-side. Understand when to use each metric and what they tell you about a company's profitability.</p>
    </div>


    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>
      <p>EBITDA and Net Income both measure profitability, but they answer different questions.</p>

      <table class="data-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Feature</th>
            <th>EBITDA</th>
            <th>Net Income</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>What it measures</strong></td>
            <td>Core operating profitability and cash generation proxy.</td>
            <td>True "bottom-line" profit available to shareholders.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Includes Interest & Taxes?</strong></td>
            <td>No. Ignores capital structure and tax rates.</td>
            <td>Yes. Fully accounts for debt and tax burden.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Includes D&A?</strong></td>
            <td>No. Ignores non-cash capital expenditures and amortization.</td>
            <td>Yes. Reduces profit based on asset wear and tear.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>When to use it</strong></td>
            <td>M&A valuation, comparing companies with different debt levels.</td>
            <td>Assessing true profitability, EPS calculation.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Pros and Cons</h2>
      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>EBITDA</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Easy to compare peer companies.</li>
            <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Shows core operational strength.</li>
            <li><strong>Con:</strong> Ignores heavy debt burdens.</li>
            <li><strong>Con:</strong> Ignores real costs of capital equipment.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Net Income</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Exact amount added to retained earnings.</li>
            <li><strong>Pro:</strong> Required for EPS and P/E ratios.</li>
            <li><strong>Con:</strong> Can be skewed by tax credits.</li>
            <li><strong>Con:</strong> D&A accounting can obscure actual cash flow.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Scenario: Positive EBITDA, Negative Net Income</h2>
      <p>Imagine a telecom company building out a 5G network. It generates $500 million in EBITDA from operations. However, it borrowed heavily to build the network, incurring $200 million in interest expense. Furthermore, the massive equipment investment causes $400 million in depreciation expense.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>EBITDA:</strong> $500 million</li>
        <li><strong>Interest:</strong> -$200 million</li>
        <li><strong>Depreciation:</strong> -$400 million</li>
        <li><strong>Net Income:</strong> -$100 million (Loss)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>This company is operationally profitable but losing money overall due to its debt and capital intensity.</p>
    </div>
<section class="related-guides">
  <h2>Related EBITDA Guides</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/ebitda-calculator">EBITDA Calculator</a></li>
    <li><a href="/what-is-ebitda-margin">What is EBITDA Margin?</a></li>
    <li><a href="/ebitda-vs-revenue">EBITDA vs Revenue</a></li>
    <li><a href="/adjusted-ebitda">Adjusted EBITDA Explained</a></li>
    <li><a href="/debt-to-ebitda-ratio">Debt to EBITDA Ratio</a></li>
    <li><a href="/good-ebitda-margin">What is a Good EBITDA Margin?</a></li>
    <li><a href="/ev-ebitda-sectors">EV/EBITDA by Sector</a></li>
  </ul>
</section>    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Is EBITDA the same as Net Income?</summary>
        <p>No. Net income is the absolute 'bottom line' profit after all expenses, including interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization. EBITDA adds those four non-operating expenses back into net income.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can a company have positive EBITDA but negative net income?</summary>
        <p>Yes. If a company has high depreciation from heavy capital investments or high interest payments from heavy debt, those expenses can push net income below zero even if operations generate positive cash (EBITDA).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Which is better for valuation: EBITDA or Net Income?</summary>
        <p>EBITDA is often preferred for valuing companies (e.g., EV/EBITDA) because it normalizes differences in capital structure and tax rates, making it easier to compare businesses.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

    <style is:inline>
      .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
      .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
      .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
      .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

      .calculator-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
      @media (min-width: 768px) { .calculator-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; } }

      .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; }
      .calc-header { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 1rem; }
      .calc-header h2 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin: 0 0 0.25rem 0; }
      .calc-header p { margin: 0; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; }

      .input-group { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
      .input-group label { display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.95rem; }
      input { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
      input:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }

      .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-top: 2rem; text-align: center; }
      .result-card.secondary { background: color-mix(in srgb, #10b981 10%, transparent); border-color: #10b981; }
      .result-card h3 { margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0; font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
      .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); }
      .secondary .result-value { color: #10b981; }

      .explainer { margin: 3rem 0; line-height: 1.6; }
      .explainer h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin: 2rem 0 1rem; }
      .explainer h3 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem; }
      .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
      .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); padding-left: 1.5rem; }
      .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

      .data-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 2rem 0; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; overflow: hidden; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0,0,0,0.1); }
      .data-table th, .data-table td { padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
      .data-table th { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); font-weight: bold; }
      .data-table tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }

      .related-guides { margin: 4rem 0; padding: 2rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
      .related-guides h2 { margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-size: 1.5rem; }
      .related-guides ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 1rem; }
      @media (min-width: 600px) { .related-guides ul { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; } }
      .related-guides a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; padding: 0.5rem; display: block; border-radius: 6px; transition: background 0.2s; }
      .related-guides a:hover { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); }

      .faq-section { margin-top: 3rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-top: 2rem; }
      .faq-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
      .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
      .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
      .faq-section details p { margin: 1rem 0 0 0; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.5; }

      .formula-visual { text-align: center; margin: 3rem 0; }
      .visual-boxes { display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; }
      .visual-boxes .box { background: var(--card-bg); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); font-weight: bold; min-width: 100px; }
      .visual-boxes .box.highlight { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border-color: var(--accent-color); color: var(--accent-color); }
      .visual-boxes .math-op { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: bold; }
    </style>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
